<subSubSection id="C30565DE2D6985483DDDFCD5274B1750" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA036552D6985483DDDFCD5274B1750" blockId="45.[192,1440,803,891]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483DDDFCD5270A1710" bold="true" box="[192,347,803,827]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">Etymology.</emphasis>
In Greek mythology, Hestia was the goddess of the hearth and sister of Hera, after which a very similar species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D6985483CA6FCB224701770" authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[443,545,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483CA6FCB224701770" box="[443,545,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was apparently named. This alludes to the close relationships of these two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30565DE2D6985483DDDFC5522BE1790" box="[192,1263,931,956]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA036552D6985483DDDFC5522BE1790" blockId="45.[192,1263,931,956]" box="[192,1263,931,956]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483DDDFC5524161790" bold="true" box="[192,583,931,955]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">Distribution and phenology.</emphasis>
The species is known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54A488F72D6985483EE2FC5222641797" box="[1023,1077,932,956]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">type</typeStatus>
taken in April.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30565DE2D6985483DDDFC15277A10F0" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA036552D6985483DDDFC15277A10F0" blockId="45.[192,1440,995,1243]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483DDDFC15247617D0" bold="true" box="[192,551,995,1019]" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis and discussion.</emphasis>
With the paucity of material, an attempt to superficially distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D698548389EFC12275B1030" authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hestia">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D698548389EFC12275B1030" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. hestia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D6985483C4EFBF227ED1030" authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[339,444,1027,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483C4EFBF227ED1030" box="[339,444,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is perhaps premature. These only suggest that 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D6985483917FBF222281030" authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[1034,1145,1027,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hestia">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483917FBF222281030" box="[1034,1145,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. hestia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger than 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D698548382DFBF223C81030" authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1328,1433,1027,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D698548382DFBF223C81030" box="[1328,1433,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has smaller macules on both the dorsal forewing and hindwing, and is more orange on the venter compared with the olivish aspect of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D6985483F5DFBB224F71070" authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[576,678,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483F5DFBB224F71070" box="[576,678,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genitalia, however, are diagnostic. Female 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D69854839EEFBB2230E1070" authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[1267,1375,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hestia">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D69854839EEFBB2230E1070" box="[1267,1375,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. hestia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the caudal lobes on the lamella postvaginalis more broadly spaced than on 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D698548390DFB9222211050" authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1040,1136,1123,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D698548390DFB9222211050" box="[1040,1136,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the lamella antevaginalis is more deeply excavate, and the ductus bursae is more constricted centrally in ventral view and has thinner internal sclerotized plates. Additionally, the corpus bursae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1F4DD62D6985483EE1FB5222361090" authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[1020,1127,1187,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hestia">
<emphasis id="B96BEA472D6985483EE1FB5222361090" box="[1020,1127,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="44">N. hestia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears shorter and more compact.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
